      <h2>Chairman's Report Autumn 2016</h2>
      <h2><a class="anchor" id="top"name="blessings"></a>Sanderstead Blessings</h4>
        <p>It is time to count our blessings. Although under pressure to provide more homes, Sanderstead has much to offer over other areas of South Croydon. Prior to the building of Sanderstead Station in 1884 Sanderstead was generally farmland with tenanted farms and a Lord of the Manor. With the opening of the station, development commenced with the specific intention of what was then considered building middle class homes. Detached houses with generous gardens now cover large areas of Sanderstead.</p>

        <p>The satellite map of Sanderstead shows a predominance of green grass and trees. We know from the Croydon Local Plan that 60% of Croydon is made up of open space, 35% of which are residents’ gardens. For Sanderstead it could be 80% open space and 45% gardens. Our open space includes Kings Wood, Sanderstead Recreation Ground, Purley Beeches, The Plantation, the Gruffy, Wettern Tree Gardens and many smaller grassed and tree areas. On our boundaries we also benefit from Croham Hurst, Riddlesdown and three golf courses.</p>

        <p>Ours is a healthy environment, especially those living in the Village through to Hamsey Green being 567 feet above sea level. During the days of the heavy smogs once you started to climb Sanderstead Hill the air would clear and you would emerge into sunlight.</p>

        <p>Not to be forgotten is our rail service. Since 1884 trains have taken Sanderstead commuters to their workplace. For the first seventy years it was steam followed by diesel  and now electric trains deliver them at Victoria or London Bridge in 30 or 35 minutes, Southern Rail permitting. For those living in walking distance of our two stations, commuting to work was often quicker than for those who lived closer to the City.</p>

        <p>Sanderstead in the main is a safe place to live with little crime in comparison to other parts of Croydon. Only seven burglaries and three motor vehicle thefts have been recorded by our police Safer Neighbourhood Team in the last three months.</p> 

        <p>We do have some issues where young people congregate in the late evening in Wettern Tree Gardens, Sanderstead Recreation Ground, Purley Beeches and Kings Wood. The Safer Neighbourhood Team patrol these areas and have made it a priority work to reduce all anti-social behaviour.  The car park to All Saints’ Church Halls was a late night hot spot for youths playing loud music from car radios whilst in the car park.   The car park is now closed by a chain link fence at the end of the evening.  This has prevented disruption to residents late into the evening.</p>

        <p>We do have issues with commuter traffic inconsiderate car parking, litter, unswept roads and problems getting the contractor to maintain the verges. The footpaths leading to Sanderstead station should be swept of wet slippery leaves and we want to ensure the council holds the contractor to account. Our councillors quite often have to intervene! We are, however, very fortunate to live in a very pleasant environment. Let us endeavor to retain it!</p>

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top"name="agm"></a>AGM 28th April, 2016</h4>
        <p>Having commenced life as the Sanderstead Ratepayer’s Association in 1926 members were welcomed to the SRA’s 90th Annual General Meeting. In attendance was Chris Philp MP and Cllr Steve O’Connell GLAM for Croydon and Sutton.</p>

        <p>Reports were presented by Mike Leach our Secretary on matters regarding planning, Sanderstead Library and the new SRA notice boards.</p>

        <p>John Kempsell our Treasurer presented the Accounts commenting that our finances were stable with advertising revenue covering the cost of producing the two annual editions of The News magazine. The membership numbers continued to increase and we held a surplus of circa £44k at the end of the financial year. The Treasurer expressed thanks to our Auditor Indrani Balanchandran.</p>

        <p>Chris Philp MP gave a report on his first year as an MP including his main campaigns regarding the abysmal Southern Rail service, the need to restore the Urgent Care Centre at Purley Hospital and his objections to the completely out of scale proposal to build a 17 storey building in the centre of Purley. This was followed by Cllr Steve O’Connell GLAM, who advised on the forthcoming elections for the Greater London Assembly.</p>
