        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="plan"></a>The Croydon local plan</h4>
        <p>Councillor Tim Pollard’s review of the Croydon Local Plan elsewhere in the News brings us some good news. The gypsy and traveller sites proposed for Conduit Lane, Coombe Farm and Pear Tree Farm are now removed, but at the cost of a closer to home traveller site now proposed at the Purley Oaks Depot (off Purley Downs Road).</p>

        <p>A number of serious threats remain. Why would the Green Belt status be removed from Croham Hurst Woods, Sanderstead Plantation and Purley Downs. Similarly, West Hill losing its Local Area of Special Character was quickly followed by a planning application to build flats on the end of West Hill opposite Croham Hurst. The application was removed after a substantial number of objections were lodged with the Croydon Planning Department but a second application would not be a surprise to us.</p>

        <p>Cllr Tim Pollard advises us that we have one last chance to change these onerous proposals. Individual objections are the most effective and the consultation process is from the 5th September for a six week period. Do read Cllr Tim Pollard’s article in the Sanderstead News magazine which explains how to comment on the proposals.</p> 

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="hospital"></a>Purley Memorial Hospital</h4>
        <p>The Croydon Clinical Commissioning Group have announced that a new GP Hub is to be opened in April 2017 at the Purley Hospital.   The successful bidder for the provision of the three Croydon GP Hubs is the Croydon Urgent Care Alliance which is a partnership of the Croydon Health Services Trust, Croydon GP Collaborative and AT Medics.</p>

        <p>The GP Hubs will be located at Purley, New Addington and a location in Central Croydon.  All three hubs will be open from 8am to 8pm for 365 days a year.</p> 

        <p>Further emergency health support will include a roving GP service for home visits, an out of hours GP service and greater use of the NHS 111 telephone service.</p> 

        <p>This follows two years of vigorous consultations attended by the eight South Croydon Residents’ Associations, following the closure of the excellent Purley Urgent Care Centre which was replaced by the inadequate Minor Injuries Unit which was open from 2pm to 8pm.</p>

        <p>The South Croydon Residents’ Associations are now working closely with the Croydon Urgent Care Alliance to finalise the details of the service prior to its publication. We are very fortunate to have a team of dedicated members of the RAs who with the enthusiastic help of Chris Philp MP have brought a working partnership with the health authority to fruition.</p>  

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="planning"></a>Planning Issues</h4>
        <p><b>Lidl at the Good Companions Site, Hamsey Green</b></p>

        <p>Lidl’s Appeal against Croydon Council’s decision to refuse their application to build a supermarket on the former Good Companion’s site was subsequently dismissed by the Planning Inspector. A second application to build a supermarket which included the purchase of two houses in Tithe Pit Shaw Lane to allow a proposal for vehicle access exiting the store opposite Hamsey Green Junior school has also been refused. Well done Croydon Planners and those who campaigned against the unsuitable application.</p>

        <p><b>Railway Land behind Norman Avenue</b></p>

        <p>It has been close to a year since an application for this badly conceived development was submitted for planning approval. For the residents in Norman and Derrick Avenues I have every sympathy for their stressful circumstances in having to wait for a decision in what could be most detrimental to their local environment.</p> 

        <p><b>McCarthy &amp; Stone Application , Addington Road</b></p>

        <p>The plan to build 32 dwellings with communal facilities on the site of four houses on the Addington Road was refused by Croydon Council on planning grounds.</p>  

        <p>McCarthy and Stone appealed against the Council’s refusal to approve their proposal to build 32 retirement apartments for older persons, with communal facilities. The Inspector dismissed the Appeal, but indicated the reason for the dismissal was a technical matter.</p>

        <p>McCarthy and Stone have announced that a new submission is to be submitted to the Council for consideration and have invited intending purchasers to register their interest should the application be approved.</p>

        <p><em>The Sanderstead Residents’ Association match funded a number of projects and plans undertaken in conjunction with the councillor’s community budgets:</em></p>

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="festival"></a>The Sanderstead Festival</h4>
        <p>Councillor Lynne Hale’s report on the Festival gives you the detail and compliments to all those who made it a success. We were delighted to work alongside All Saints’ Church, the local councillors and the community on this exciting project.  It was wonderful to see so many people flowing to and from the Church, Church Halls, The Gruffy and the Cricket Ground. A sign of its success are people, performers and stall holders asking us whether we will do this again!</p>

        <p>The evening performance of the Nigel Garrard Big Band was a rare opportunity to hear live swing music reviving memories of Glen Miller, Ted Heath, Woody Herman and other great bands.  The evening was sponsored by the SRA and the proceeds will go to our local charities, local good causes and youth groups.</p>

        <p>This was an outstanding community venture which required leadership, co-operation of many and enthusiasm. Thank you to Cllr Lynne Hale and all those involved.</p>

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="pond"></a>Hamsey Green Pond</h4>
        <p>We were also pleased to support the work at Hamsey Green pond.  A new sign has been installed and two new benches for all to enjoy.  Do read Cllr Yvette Hopley’s report on progress to-date and further plans to improve the area and biodiversity.</p>

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="flood"></a>Flood Protection</h4>
        <p>We jointly funded a new “flood gate” to help alleviate problems with flooding of the scout hut.  The Council are looking at further prevention and a CCTV investigation has been undertaken to assess the problems with the drainage system and how water can be diverted more efficiently into the soakaway into the grounds rather than the hut!</p>

        <h4><a class="anchor" id="top" name="lights"></a>Christmas Lights</h4>
        <p>A further joint project to install Christmas lights on the new lamp columns is underway.  Estimates are being obtained and we hope to have a festive feel to Sanderstead this coming Christmas so watch this space!</p>

        <p>It has been a busy and eventful year for the Residents’ Association and we are very much looking forward to supporting the community next year and are sure that we will be able to update you with further exciting projects in 2017.</p>

        <p>Do keep up-to-date with all our reports on this Sanderstead Residents’ Association website, kindly run by Corrie Hibberd.</p>









        
